d but by God's wisdom and law\n\n- John Bunyan, The Pilgrim's Progress\n|\nThere is a candle in your heart, ready to be kindled.There is a void in your soul, ready to be filled.You feel it, don't you?\n\n- Jalaluddin\n|\nAd we interviewing each other?Something like that.What position am I applying for?Best friend.I thought I already had the job.Don't be so sure, you arrogant son of a bitch.\n\n- Benjamin Alire Sáenz, Aristotle and Dante Discover the Secrets of the Universe\n|\nIt's easy to talk big, but the important thing is whether or not you clean up the shit.\n\n- Haruki Murakami, Norwegian Wood\n|\nWar is father of all, and king of all. He renders some gods, others men; he makes some slaves, others free.\n\n- Heraclitus, Fragments\n|\nIt is one of the strongest bonds, I think, that can spring up between people: sharing a passion for certain books and their authors.\n\n- Alice Steinbach, Without Reservations: The Travels of an Independent Woman\n|\nWrite like it matters, and it will.\n\n- Libba\n|\nYou see, there are some people that one loves, and others that perhaps one would rather be with.\n\n- Henrik Ibsen, A Doll's House\n|\nWell if God wanted a broken spirit out of me, He would get Hiswish. At this point in my life the only thing I could do was look up.\n\n- Michelle Sutton, Never Without Hope\n|\nWe're staying together,' he promised. 'You're not getting away from me. Never again.\n\n- Rick Riordan, The Mark of Athena\n|\nIn displaying the psychology of your characters, minute particulars are essential. God save us from vague generalizations!', May 10, 1886)\n\n- Anton\n|\nI wish I had never been born,' she said. 'What are we born for?' 'For infinite happiness,' said the Spirit. 'You can step out into it at any moment...\n\n- C.S. Lewis, The Great Divorce\n|\nThis is where people misunderstand war. When you attack another country for its resources, you are the pirate. But when you protect your country from the pirates, you are the hero.\n\n- Suzy Kassem, 